@zardus I agree, the name `TechniqueBuilder` would suite better. It actually makes more clear what's this technique is designed for.

@rhelmot Unfortunately, the ability of altering the simulation manager behavior using the `step()` parameters is somewhat limited and doesn't cover all the situations that one might encounter. For example, the `successor_func` you mentioned before doesn't allow modifications of the stashes prior to the first call to `_one_step()` method, as could be seen in _manager.py_:
```
            # Lines 604-606
            pg = pg._one_step(stash=stash, selector_func=selector_func, successor_func=successor_func, **kwargs)
            if step_func is not None:
                pg = step_func(pg)
```
Another example of limited functionality would be the absence of a `filter_func` in the parameters of `step()` function, thus making one unable to use the internal filtering functionality. This example, of course, could be argued over, as one could implement the custom filtering using the `successors_func`. However, in that case, it's become unclear, in what order the calls to different filter routines should happen. The latter statement is applicable to any arbitrary set exploration techniques, which are using the `step()` `*_func` parameters, and which are setup to be used simultaneously.

And finally, those individual parameters passed to `step()` method could influence only a very particular aspects of stepping process, which might be not enough for one to implement the desired stepping logic. Yet, those changes might be too special-case and ad-hoc-like for them to be done in form of a separate exploration technique.

@axt The particular example you provided could actually run slower in some special case, because the `step_func` and exploration technique `step` override are handled rather differently inside the simulation manager. 

The first example, that comes to my mind, is that the evaluation of `path.addr == addr` condition does   involve a lot of constraint solving, (if I remember correctly, the `path.addr` property was hiding a call to `state.se.any_int(state.ip)` inside), and when the `pg.stash` is called _after_ the first call to `_one_step()` routine (see the above example), it causes a severe slow-down of the whole process. On the other side, when implemented as an exploration technique, the call to `pg.stash` happens _before_ the simulation manager internal stepping logic kicks in, as could be seen in the `_one_step()` implementation details, thus now having the same impact.

Obligatory warning that may not apply in your case: Depending on the calling convention, skipping function calls can result in the stack pointer becoming corrupted.

For example, in your example there are two `push`es before the `call`. If the callee is responsible for cleaning up the stack (e.g., `ret 8`) then simply NOPing out the call instruction with an empty hook will cause the stack to become corrupt. The correct thing to do in that case is to stub the function with a SimProcedure while specifying the calling convention.

@rhelmot has some code that can help to [automatically detect calling conventions](https://github.com/angr/angr/blob/master/angr/analyses/callee_cleanup_finder.py). In particular it will attempt to determine the size of the stack that the callee will cleanup before returning. It is mostly helpful when stubbing functions in a Windows binary. It works very well. The only discrepancy I have had was for a function in a dll that takes one of two paths: It either returns to the caller, or calls a function that does not return. This is more of a CFG problem though.

